entry.title: Unsupervised ML with PCA
entry.summary: In this section I am using the unsupervised algorithm called "PCA" which is called as "Principal components analysis".PCA is used on the correlated data and make them uncorrelated dataset.In this blog we will use the PCA on the 3D modelling of the armadillo which shows the structure of the armadillo and I will try to use PCA make it a 2D structure.The package I am going to use are:

<div class="text_cell_render border-box-sizing rendered_html">
<p>In this section I am using the unsupervised algorithm called "PCA" which is called as "Principal components analysis".PCA is used on the correlated data and make them uncorrelated dataset.In this blog we will use the PCA on the 3D modelling of the armadillo which shows the structure of the armadillo and I will try to use PCA make it a 2D structure.The package I am going to use are:</p>
<p>1.pandas(dataframe manipulation)</p>
<p>2.Matplotlib(visualization tool)</p>
<p>3.Plyfile to load the 3d model data.</p>
<h5 id="Definition:">Definition:<a class="anchor-link" href="#Definition:">¶</a></h5><p>Principal component analysis (PCA) is a statistical procedure that uses an orthogonal transformation to convert a set of observations of possibly correlated variables into a set of values of linearly uncorrelated variables called principal components (or sometimes, principal modes of variation).#Wikipedia</p>
<h6 id="How-It-works:">How It works:<a class="anchor-link" href="#How-It-works:">¶</a></h6><p>PCA is one of the most popular techniques for dimensionality reduction. It models a linear subspace of our data by capturing its greatest variability. Stated differently, it accesses our dataset's covariance structure directly using matrix calculations and eigenvectors to compute the best unique features that describe our samples.</p>
<p>An iterative approach to this would first find the center of our data, based off its numeric features. Next, it would search for the direction that has the most variance or widest spread of values. That direction is the principal component vector, so it is then added to a list. By searching for more directions of maximal variance that are orthogonal to all previously computed vectors, more principal component can then be added to the list. This set of vectors form a new feature space that we can represent our samples with.</p>
<p>You can see how the PCA work in figure below.</p>

<div class="cell border-box-sizing text_cell rendered"><div class="prompt input_prompt">
</div>
<div class="inner_cell">
<div class="text_cell_render border-box-sizing rendered_html">
<p>In the above 2D dataset, the orange line represents the principal component direction, and the gray line represents the second principal component. The one that's going to get dropped:</p>
<p>1.By dropping the gray component above, the goal is to project the 2D points onto 1D space. Move the original 2D samples to their closest spot on the line.</p>
<p>2.Once you've projected all samples to their closest spot on the major principal component, a shadow, or lower dimensional representation has been formed.</p>
<p>3.The summed distances traveled by all moved samples is equal to the total information lost by the projection. An an ideal situation, this lost information should be dominated by highly redundant features and random noise.</p>
</div>
</div>
</div>
<div class="cell border-box-sizing code_cell rendered">
<div class="input">
<div class="prompt input_prompt">In [60]:</div>
<div class="inner_cell">
<div class="input_area">
<div class=" highlight hl-ipython3"><pre><span></span><span class="c1">#loading up package</span>
<span class="kn">import</span> <span class="nn">pandas</span> <span class="k">as</span> <span class="nn">pd</span>
<span class="kn">import</span> <span class="nn">matplotlib.pyplot</span> <span class="k">as</span> <span class="nn">plt</span>
<span class="kn">import</span> <span class="nn">matplotlib</span>

<span class="kn">from</span> <span class="nn">mpl_toolkits.mplot3d</span> <span class="k">import</span> <span class="n">Axes3D</span>
<span class="kn">from</span> <span class="nn">plyfile</span> <span class="k">import</span> <span class="n">PlyData</span><span class="p">,</span> <span class="n">PlyElement</span>
<span class="c1"># matplotlib.style.use('ggplot') </span>
<span class="c1">#ggplot is a R language visualization program</span>
<span class="n">plt</span><span class="o">.</span><span class="n">style</span><span class="o">.</span><span class="n">use</span><span class="p">(</span><span class="s1">'ggplot'</span><span class="p">)</span>
</pre></div>
</div>
</div>
</div>

</div>
<div class="inner_cell">
<div class="text_cell_render border-box-sizing rendered_html">
<p>For Every <code>100</code> samples in the dataset, I save <code>1</code>.</p>
</div>
</div>
</div>

<div class="input">

<div class="inner_cell">
<div class="input_area">
<div class=" highlight hl-ipython3"><pre><span></span><span class="n">reduce_factor</span> <span class="o">=</span> <span class="mi">100</span>
</pre></div>
</div>
</div>
</div>
</div>
<div class="cell border-box-sizing text_cell rendered"><div class="prompt input_prompt">
</div>
<div class="inner_cell">
<div class="text_cell_render border-box-sizing rendered_html">
<p>Load up the scanned armadillo:</p>
</div>
</div>
</div>
<div class="cell border-box-sizing code_cell rendered">
<div class="input">
<div class="prompt input_prompt">In [62]:</div>
<div class="inner_cell">
<div class="input_area">
<div class=" highlight hl-ipython3"><pre><span></span><span class="n">plyfile</span> <span class="o">=</span> <span class="n">PlyData</span><span class="o">.</span><span class="n">read</span><span class="p">(</span><span class="s1">'Datasets/stanford_armadillo.ply'</span><span class="p">)</span>
<span class="c1">#making dataframe of the armadilllo 3d model</span>
<span class="n">armadillo</span> <span class="o">=</span> <span class="n">pd</span><span class="o">.</span><span class="n">DataFrame</span><span class="p">({</span>
  <span class="s1">'x'</span><span class="p">:</span><span class="n">plyfile</span><span class="p">[</span><span class="s1">'vertex'</span><span class="p">][</span><span class="s1">'z'</span><span class="p">][::</span><span class="n">reduce_factor</span><span class="p">],</span>
  <span class="s1">'y'</span><span class="p">:</span><span class="n">plyfile</span><span class="p">[</span><span class="s1">'vertex'</span><span class="p">][</span><span class="s1">'x'</span><span class="p">][::</span><span class="n">reduce_factor</span><span class="p">],</span>
  <span class="s1">'z'</span><span class="p">:</span><span class="n">plyfile</span><span class="p">[</span><span class="s1">'vertex'</span><span class="p">][</span><span class="s1">'y'</span><span class="p">][::</span><span class="n">reduce_factor</span><span class="p">]</span>
<span class="p">})</span>
</pre></div>

<div class="cell border-box-sizing text_cell rendered"><div class="prompt input_prompt">
</div>
<div class="inner_cell">
<div class="text_cell_render border-box-sizing rendered_html">
<h3 id="PCA">PCA<a class="anchor-link" href="#PCA">¶</a></h3>
</div>
</div>
</div>
<div class="cell border-box-sizing text_cell rendered"><div class="prompt input_prompt">
</div>
<div class="inner_cell">
<div class="text_cell_render border-box-sizing rendered_html">
<p>In the method below, code to import the libraries required for PCA.</p>
<p>Then, I train a PCA model on the passed in <code>armadillo</code> dataframe parameter. Lastly, project the armadillo down to the two principal components, by dropping one dimension.</p>
<p>For additional details, please read through <a href="http://scikit-learn.org/stable/modules/generated/sklearn.decomposition.PCA.html">Decomposition - PCA</a>.</p>
<p>In this section I am using the PCA algorithm to transform the model to 2D.</p>
</div>
</div>
</div>
<div class="cell border-box-sizing code_cell rendered">
<div class="input">
<div class="prompt input_prompt">In [63]:</div>
<div class="inner_cell">
<div class="input_area">
<div class=" highlight hl-ipython3"><pre><span></span><span class="k">def</span> <span class="nf">do_PCA</span><span class="p">(</span><span class="n">armadillo</span><span class="p">,</span> <span class="n">svd_solver</span><span class="p">):</span>
    <span class="kn">from</span> <span class="nn">sklearn.decomposition</span> <span class="k">import</span> <span class="n">PCA</span>
    <span class="n">pca</span> <span class="o">=</span> <span class="n">PCA</span><span class="p">(</span><span class="n">n_components</span> <span class="o">=</span> <span class="mi">2</span><span class="p">)</span> 
    <span class="n">pca</span><span class="o">.</span><span class="n">fit</span><span class="p">(</span><span class="n">armadillo</span><span class="p">)</span>
    <span class="n">result</span> <span class="o">=</span> <span class="n">pca</span><span class="o">.</span><span class="n">transform</span><span class="p">(</span><span class="n">armadillo</span><span class="p">)</span>
    <span class="k">return</span> <span class="n">result</span>
</pre></div>
</div>
</div>
</div>
</div>

<div class=" highlight hl-ipython3"><pre><span></span><span class="c1"># Render the Original Armadillo</span>

</div>
<div class="inner_cell">
<div class="text_cell_render border-box-sizing rendered_html">
<p>In the figure above you can see the 3D Model of Armadilo with green dots whose face facing toward left of X-axis.</p>
</div>
</div>
</div>
<div class="cell border-box-sizing text_cell rendered"><div class="prompt input_prompt">
</div>
<div class="inner_cell">
<div class="text_cell_render border-box-sizing rendered_html">
<h3 id="Time-Execution-Speeds">Time Execution Speeds<a class="anchor-link" href="#Time-Execution-Speeds">¶</a></h3>
</div>
</div>
</div>
<div class="cell border-box-sizing text_cell rendered"><div class="prompt input_prompt">
</div>
<div class="inner_cell">
<div class="text_cell_render border-box-sizing rendered_html">
<p>Let's see how long it takes PCA to execute:</p>
</div>
</div>
</div>
<div class="cell border-box-sizing code_cell rendered">
<div class="input">
<div class="prompt input_prompt">In [65]:</div>
<div class="inner_cell">
<div class="input_area">
<div class=" highlight hl-ipython3"><pre><span></span><span class="o">%</span><span class="k">timeit</span>  pca = do_PCA(armadillo,'auto')
</pre></div>
</div>
</div>
</div>
<div class="output_wrapper">
<div class="output">
<div class="output_area">
<div class="prompt"></div>
<div class="output_subarea output_stream output_stdout output_text">
<pre>2.39 ms ± 255 µs per loop (mean ± std. dev. of 7 runs, 100 loops each)
</pre>
</div>
</div>
</div>
</div>
</div>
<div class="cell border-box-sizing text_cell rendered"><div class="prompt input_prompt">
</div>
<div class="inner_cell">
<div class="text_cell_render border-box-sizing rendered_html">
<p>Render the newly transformed PCA armadillo!</p>
</div>
</div>
</div>
<div class="cell border-box-sizing code_cell rendered">
<div class="input">
<div class="prompt input_prompt">In [66]:</div>
<div class="inner_cell">
<div class="input_area">
<div class=" highlight hl-ipython3"><pre><span></span><span class="n">fig</span> <span class="o">=</span> <span class="n">plt</span><span class="o">.</span><span class="n">figure</span><span class="p">(</span><span class="n">figsize</span><span class="o">=</span><span class="p">[</span><span class="mi">10</span><span class="p">,</span><span class="mi">5</span><span class="p">])</span>

<span class="n">ax</span><span class="o">.</span><span class="n">set_title</span><span class="p">(</span><span class="s1">'Full PCA'</span><span class="p">)</span>
<span class="n">ax</span><span class="o">.</span><span class="n">scatter</span><span class="p">(</span><span class="n">pca</span><span class="p">[:,</span><span class="mi">0</span><span class="p">],</span> <span class="n">pca</span><span class="p">[:,</span><span class="mi">1</span><span class="p">],</span> <span class="n">c</span><span class="o">=</span><span class="s1">'blue'</span><span class="p">,</span> <span class="n">marker</span><span class="o">=</span><span class="s1">'.'</span><span class="p">,</span> <span class="n">alpha</span><span class="o">=</span><span class="mf">0.75</span><span class="p">)</span>
<span class="n">plt</span><span class="o">.</span><span class="n">show</span><span class="p">()</span>
</pre></div>
</div>

</div>
<div class="inner_cell">
<div class="text_cell_render border-box-sizing rendered_html">
<p>The above picture is the plot of the dataframe that I got after using Normal or Full PCA algorithm.In this figure I got the 2D image of 3D model which seems like plot of Y,Z axis of previous 3D model but it is plot of the point we got after dimensionality reduction.</p>
</div>
</div>
</div>
<div class="cell border-box-sizing text_cell rendered"><div class="prompt input_prompt">
</div>
<div class="inner_cell">
<div class="text_cell_render border-box-sizing rendered_html">
<p>Let's also take a look at the speed of the randomized solver on the same dataset. It might be faster, it might be slower, or it might take exactly the same amount of time to execute:
Let's see what the results look like:</p>
</div>
</div>
</div>
<div class="cell border-box-sizing code_cell rendered">
<div class="input">
<div class="prompt input_prompt">In [67]:</div>
<div class="inner_cell">
<div class="input_area">
<div class=" highlight hl-ipython3"><pre><span></span><span class="k">def</span> <span class="nf">do_RANDOMPCA</span><span class="p">(</span><span class="n">armadillo</span><span class="p">):</span>
    <span class="kn">from</span> <span class="nn">sklearn.decomposition</span> <span class="k">import</span> <span class="n">RandomizedPCA</span>
    <span class="n">rpca</span> <span class="o">=</span> <span class="n">RandomizedPCA</span><span class="p">(</span><span class="n">n_components</span> <span class="o">=</span> <span class="mi">2</span><span class="p">)</span>
    <span class="n">rpca</span><span class="o">.</span><span class="n">fit</span><span class="p">(</span><span class="n">armadillo</span><span class="p">)</span>
    <span class="n">result1</span> <span class="o">=</span> <span class="n">rpca</span><span class="o">.</span><span class="n">transform</span><span class="p">(</span><span class="n">armadillo</span><span class="p">)</span>
    <span class="k">return</span> <span class="n">result1</span>
</pre></div>
</div>
</div>
</div>
</div>
<div class="cell border-box-sizing code_cell rendered">
<div class="input">
<div class="prompt input_prompt">In [68]:</div>
<div class="inner_cell">
<div class="input_area">
<div class=" highlight hl-ipython3"><pre><span></span><span class="n">rpca</span> <span class="o">=</span> <span class="n">do_PCA</span><span class="p">(</span><span class="n">armadillo</span><span class="p">,</span><span class="s1">'randomized'</span><span class="p">)</span>
<span class="n">fig</span> <span class="o">=</span> <span class="n">plt</span><span class="o">.</span><span class="n">figure</span><span class="p">(</span><span class="n">figsize</span><span class="o">=</span><span class="p">[</span><span class="mi">10</span><span class="p">,</span><span class="mi">5</span><span class="p">])</span>
<span class="n">ax</span> <span class="o">=</span> <span class="n">fig</span><span class="o">.</span><span class="n">add_subplot</span><span class="p">(</span><span class="mi">111</span><span class="p">)</span>
<span class="n">ax</span><span class="o">.</span><span class="n">set_title</span><span class="p">(</span><span class="s1">'Randomized PCA'</span><span class="p">)</span>
<span class="n">ax</span><span class="o">.</span><span class="n">scatter</span><span class="p">(</span><span class="n">rpca</span><span class="p">[:,</span><span class="mi">0</span><span class="p">],</span> <span class="n">rpca</span><span class="p">[:,</span><span class="mi">1</span><span class="p">],</span> <span class="n">c</span><span class="o">=</span><span class="s1">'red'</span><span class="p">,</span> <span class="n">marker</span><span class="o">=</span><span class="s1">'.'</span><span class="p">,</span> <span class="n">alpha</span><span class="o">=</span><span class="mf">0.75</span><span class="p">)</span>
<span class="n">plt</span><span class="o">.</span><span class="n">show</span><span class="p">()</span>
</pre></div>
</div>
</div>

entry.title: Iris dataset and ML with Sklearn
entry.summary:
Iris dataset and ML with Sklearn¶

In this blog I am will use some machine learning concept with help of ScikitLearn(sklearn) an Machine Learning Package and Iris dataset which can be loaded from sklearn ,use numpy to work on the Iris dataset and Matplotlib for Visualization.

Iris dataset is a multivariate data set introduced by the British statistician and biologist Ronald Fisher in his 1936 paper The use of multiple measurements in taxonomic problems as an example of linear discriminant analysis.The data set consists of 50 samples from each of three species of Iris (Iris setosa, Iris virginica and Iris versicolor).Four features were measured from each sample: the length and the width of the sepals and petals, in centimetres.

<h2 id="Iris-dataset-and-ML-with-Sklearn">Iris dataset and ML with Sklearn<a class="anchor-link" href="#Iris-dataset-and-ML-with-Sklearn">¶</a></h2><p>In this blog I am   will use some machine learning concept with help of ScikitLearn(sklearn) an Machine Learning Package and Iris dataset which can be loaded from sklearn ,use numpy to work on the Iris dataset and Matplotlib for Visualization.</p>
<p>Iris dataset is a multivariate data set introduced by the British statistician and biologist Ronald Fisher in his 1936 paper The use of multiple measurements in taxonomic problems as an example of linear discriminant analysis.The data set consists of 50 samples from each of three species of Iris (Iris setosa, Iris virginica and Iris versicolor).Four features were measured from each sample: the length and the width of the sepals and petals, in centimetres.</p>

<div class="inner_cell">
<div class="text_cell_render border-box-sizing rendered_html">
<p>We can see the types of flowers and difference between them in above image.In this machine learing program we will denote as:</p>
<h5 id="Setosa-as-0--Versicolour-as-1--Virginica-as-2">Setosa as 0  Versicolour as 1  Virginica as 2<a class="anchor-link" href="#Setosa-as-0--Versicolour-as-1--Virginica-as-2">¶</a></h5><p>We will use sepal length , sepal width , petal length , petal width as features to identify the species of iris flower.</p>
</div>
</div>
</div>
<div class="cell border-box-sizing code_cell rendered">
<div class="input">
<div class="prompt input_prompt">In [44]:</div>
<div class="inner_cell">
<div class="input_area">
<div class=" highlight hl-ipython3"><pre><span></span><span class="o">%%</span><span class="k">time</span>
import numpy as np
from sklearn.datasets import load_iris
from sklearn import tree

iris = load_iris()
test_idx = np.random.randint(1,150, size=35)#taking random order  1/4th of dataset for testing  and remaining for training.


#training data
train_target = np.delete(iris.target, test_idx) 
train_data = np.delete(iris.data,test_idx,axis=0) #training data

#testing data
test_target = iris.target[test_idx] # required output or flower name
test_data = iris.data[test_idx] # data which will use to test the machine learning algorithm

#creating classifier
clf = tree.DecisionTreeClassifier()
clf.fit(train_data, train_target)

print (test_target); ##required result for the testing data
print (clf.predict(test_data)); ## predicted result from the classifier

test_true = test_target.tolist()
test_result = (clf.predict(test_data)).tolist()
</pre></div>
</div>
</div>
</div>

Wall time: 6.98 ms

<div class=" highlight hl-ipython3"><pre><span></span><span class="c1"># Checking the accuracy rate of the program</span>
<span class="kn">from</span> <span class="nn">sklearn.metrics</span> <span class="k">import</span> <span class="n">accuracy_score</span>
<span class="nb">print</span> <span class="p">(</span><span class="s1">'Accuracy rate'</span><span class="p">);</span>
<span class="nb">print</span> <span class="p">(</span><span class="n">accuracy_score</span><span class="p">(</span><span class="n">test_true</span><span class="p">,</span> <span class="n">test_result</span><span class="p">)</span> <span class="o">*</span> <span class="mi">100</span><span class="p">);</span>

<div class="text_cell_render border-box-sizing rendered_html">
<h3 id="Visualizing-the-features-and--clusters">Visualizing the features and  clusters<a class="anchor-link" href="#Visualizing-the-features-and--clusters">¶</a></h3><p>The Iris flower has 4 features in given datasets I am going to use those features data to make 2-D scatterplot using matplotlib.I am ploting feature vs feature scatterplot i.e Petal width vs sepal width .etc . In the below plot we label as:</p>
<h4 id="Setosa-as-Red-dot,Versicolor-as-Green-,-Virginica-as-Blue.">Setosa as Red dot,Versicolor as Green , Virginica as Blue.<a class="anchor-link" href="#Setosa-as-Red-dot,Versicolor-as-Green-,-Virginica-as-Blue.">¶</a></h4>
</div>
</div>
</div>
<div class="cell border-box-sizing code_cell rendered">
<div class="input">
<div class="prompt input_prompt">In [76]:</div>
<div class="inner_cell">
<div class="input_area">
<div class=" highlight hl-ipython3"><pre><span></span><span class="kn">import</span> <span class="nn">matplotlib.pyplot</span> <span class="k">as</span> <span class="nn">plt</span>
<span class="n">iris_data</span>  <span class="o">=</span> <span class="n">iris</span><span class="p">[</span><span class="s1">'data'</span><span class="p">]</span>
<span class="n">iris_species</span> <span class="o">=</span> <span class="n">iris</span><span class="p">[</span><span class="s1">'target'</span><span class="p">]</span>

<span class="k">def</span> <span class="nf">scaterplot</span><span class="p">(</span><span class="n">x</span><span class="p">,</span><span class="n">y</span><span class="p">):</span>

<div class="inner_cell">
<div class="text_cell_render border-box-sizing rendered_html">
<p>The above figure is called Anderson's Iris dataset visualization. 
We can the formation of 3 cluster in every figure above.In some there is clear clusters are formed and in some the cluster are very near to each other.In every scatterplot we can find that Iris setosa is much different from two other Iris flowers as Setosa cluster is far away from other two flower species.
Iris Verginica and Iris Verscicolor also formed there own cluster but they are very near each other and far from I.Setosa.
From above figure we can find that the four features provided in data are good features and they will help our model to identify the flower.If above figures don't help you to understand the clusters below are some code and visualizations which may help you.</p>
